Vector spatial features: Points, lines, and polygons in R

J. Camilo Fagua

February 2024

I. Objectives

  1. Learn the basic logic and construction of the vector spatial features (points, lines, polygons) in R.

  2. Learn some of the basic operations with vector spatial features in R.

  3. Understand the R logic to process vector spatial features.

  4. Review some of the main R packages to process vector spatial feature in R.

II. Introduction

This tutorial is focused on providing you the tools required to build, read, and project vector spatial feature in R. There are two main packages used by the R community to bring vector spatial feature data into R: 1) sp and sf. In this tutorial, we will also use the package tidyverse. Let’s go to start.

The package sp is the mama-package of all vector spatial feature packages of R. sp revolutionized the spatial analysis in R when it was built. Team sp created a set of data classes that integrates the traditional objects of R (vector, data.frame, matrix, list, and others) with the vector spatial features: points, lines, and polygons. The package sf is considered an evolution of sp; however, sp is maintained in R since many packages were built using the sp architecture, including the sf package. The plan is that sf succeeds sp in the long term.

III. Some important definitions before the scripts

Simple features: Simple feature refers to a formal standard (ISO 19125-1:2004) that describes how objects in the real world can be represented in computers, with emphasis on the spatial geometry of these objects (points, lines, polygons, pixels, raster). That is, a feature is thought of as a thing, or an object in the real world, such as a building or a tree. As with any other object, a feature often consists of other objects (features), that is, a set of features can form a single feature. A forest stand can be a feature, a forest can be a feature, a city can be a feature. A satellite image pixel can be a feature, a complete image can be a feature too (Pebesma and Bivand, 2023).

Geometry: Features (points, lines, polygons, pixels, raster) have a geometry describing where on Earth (or Cartesian plane) the feature is located, and they have attributes, which describe other properties. The geometry of a tree can be the delineation of its crown, of its stem, or the point indicating its center. Other properties may include its height, color, diameter at breast height at a particular date, and so on (Pebesma and Bivand, 2023).

Dimensions All vector geometries are composed of points. Points are coordinates in a 2-, 3- or 4-dimensional (even more) space. In addition to X and Y coordinates, there are two optional additional dimensions, Z coordinate to denote altitude, and M coordinate(s) to measure an extra variable(s).

Coordinate Reference System - CRS: CRS is a latitude-longitude projection model of the earth based on a geoid model.

Geoid: A geoid is an irregular-shaped model to accurately calculate locations on and under the earth’s surface.

Geodetic datum: Datum refers to the definition of Earth center-position in the geoid.

Spatial lines

Spatial lines are retrieved from external sources frequently; however, the following example show how to build an object of class SpatialLines from scratch. We firstly create the points that lines are going to follow. We secondly create the lines using these points and the function Line(). We thirdly put these lines in a list separately; these lines are not spatial object at this point. We finally merge both lines and give spatial properties with the function SpatialLines(). Note that the lines objects must be given character ID values, and that these values must be unique for Lines objects combined in a SpatialLines objects.

# To create the points that the lines follow. 
l1 = cbind(c(1,2,3),c(3,2,2))
l1a = cbind(l1[,1]+.05,l1[,2]+.05)
l2 = cbind(c(1,2,3),c(1,1.5,1))

# To create the lines.
Sl1 = Line(l1)
Sl1a = Line(l1a)
Sl2 = Line(l2)

# To put these lines in a list separately.
S1 = Lines(list(Sl1, Sl1a), ID="a")
S2 = Lines(list(Sl2), ID="b")
#
Sl = SpatialLines(list(S1,S2))
summary(Sl)
## Object of class SpatialLines
## Coordinates:
##   min  max
## x   1 3.05
## y   1 3.05
## Is projected: NA 
## proj4string : [NA]
plot(Sl)

We can create a SpatialLines object with attributes by attaching an attribute table (data.frame). In the next codes, the function sapply() applies the function slot() to each line object to generate an ID.

df_2 = data.frame(z = c(1,2), row.names=sapply(slot(Sl, "lines"), function(x) slot(x, "ID")))
Sldf = SpatialLinesDataFrame(Sl, data = df_2)
plot(Sldf)

Spatial Polygons

Now we will build polygons from scratch. The function cbind() allows the construction of the points that form the polygons while the function Polygon() creates no-spatial polygons. The argument hole = TRUE of Sr4 is for setting a polygon as hole.

#To create no-spatial polygons 
Sr1 = Polygon(cbind(c(2,4,4,1,2),c(2,3,5,4,2)))
Sr2 = Polygon(cbind(c(5,4,2,5),c(2,3,2,2)))
Sr3 = Polygon(cbind(c(4,4,5,10,4),c(5,3,2,5,5)))
Sr4 = Polygon(cbind(c(5,6,6,5,5),c(4,4,3,3,4)), hole = TRUE)
Sr1@coords #To see coordinates
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    2    2
## [2,]    4    3
## [3,]    4    5
## [4,]    1    4
## [5,]    2    2
#To put the polygons in a list and add IDs ("s1","s2","s3").
Srs1 = Polygons(list(Sr1), "s1")
Srs2 = Polygons(list(Sr2), "s2")
Srs3 = Polygons(list(Sr3, Sr4), "s3/s4")

Note that the Polygons objects must be given character ID values, and that these values must be unique for Polygons objects combined in a SpatialPolygons object. Now we are going to create the spatial polygon.

#To create the final spatial polygons and plot it.
SpP = SpatialPolygons(list(Srs1,Srs2,Srs3), 1:3)
plot(SpP, col = 1:3)

As we did for spatial point and lines, we can attach attributes to the spatial polygons. Polygons with attributes (objects of class SpatialPolygonsDataFrame) are built from the SpatialPolygons object (topology) and the attributes (data.frame). The row.names of the attributes data frame are matched with the ID slots of the SpatialPolygons object, and the rows of the data frame will be re-ordered if necessary.

attr = data.frame(a=1:3, row.names=c("s3/s4", "s2", "s1"))

IV. Creating spatial objects from scratch using sf

Package sf represents simple features (sf) as native R objects. All functions and methods of sf are prefixed by st_, which means spatial type. As in sp, attributes are typically stored in data.frame objects. However, geometrics are also stored in a data.frame-column in a column at sf (a list of length equal to the number of records in the data.frame).

Spatial points

The function “st_point” creates simple spatial points from a numeric vector, matrix or list. The character-argument “dim” indicates dimensions: “XY”, “XYZ”, “XYM”, or “XYZM”; only really needed for three-dimensional points (which can be either XYZ or XYM).

rm(list = ls(all.names = TRUE))

Spatial lines

Spatial lines can be built using the function st_linestring(). We firstly create the points that lines are going to follow. We secondly create the lines using these points and the function st_linestring(). When you apply this function, the created object (class: “LINESTRING-sfg”) has complete spatial properties; you can check it out by the use of the function st_coordinates(), st_bbox(), and plot(). These objects obviously do not have a CRS.

#pts1 = matrix(1:10, , 2)
pts1 = matrix(1:10, nrow = 5, byrow = F)
pts1
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    6
## [2,]    2    7
## [3,]    3    8
## [4,]    4    9
## [5,]    5   10
ls1 = st_linestring(pts1)
ls1
## LINESTRING (1 6, 2 7, 3 8, 4 9, 5 10)
class(ls1)
## [1] "XY"         "LINESTRING" "sfg"
st_coordinates(ls1)
##      X  Y L1
## [1,] 1  6  1
## [2,] 2  7  1
## [3,] 3  8  1
## [4,] 4  9  1
## [5,] 5 10  1
st_bbox(ls1)
## xmin ymin xmax ymax 
##    1    6    5   10
plot(ls1)

Spatial polygons also can be create using the function st_polygon (). We firstly create matrices that refer to the points (X,Y) that polygons are going to follow. We later create a list with these matrices to apply the function st_polygon(). The created object (class “XY-POLYGON-sfg”) has complete spatial properties; you can check it out by the use of the function st_coordinates(), st_bbox(), and plot(). Again, this object obviously does not have a CRS.

outer = matrix(c(0,0,10,0,10,10,0,10,0,0),ncol=2, byrow=TRUE)

hole2 = matrix(c(5,5,5,6,6,6,6,5,5,5),ncol=2, byrow=TRUE)
pts4 = list(outer, hole1, hole2)

V. Loading and operating existing shapefiles into R

The data required to visualize a single shapefile in Arc or QGIS is split into many files (e.g., cpg, .dbf, .prj, etc.), the most known of which is the sacred .shp file (do you know the function of the other files?). To get all this info into an organized spatial object in R is easy, and in fact, as is often the case in R, there are multiple packages and functions that will do this for you. Here are three of the most used options to read .shp of the packages raster and sf:

The attribute selection by subsetting is based on logical operators (e.g. ==, |, &, >=, $). You can find many guides to use this type of operators; one of these guides is in towards data science;. You can also subset by the interaction of attributes using logical operators. For instance, a group 1 with the departments larger than the average size (DPTO_NAREA; values in km2) that were created before 1950. Or a group 2 with the departments in the quartile 1 (the smallest) created after 1950.

#Group 1
Size = mean(DEPARTMENTS_1$DPTO_NAREA)#To obtain the mean
Size
## [1] 34574.78
GROUP_1 = subset(DEPARTMENTS_1, DPTO_NAREA >= mean(DEPARTMENTS_1$DPTO_NAREA) & DPTO_ANO_C <= 1950)

Crop(clip)

You also can crop input features that overlay a clip feature. You can use crops to cut out a piece of one feature class using one or more of the features in another feature class as a cookie cutter with the function crop(). We are going to load the .shp of the Colombian amazon region to crop the departments that are in the region.

AMAZONIA = read_sf(dsn = ".", layer = "Lim_Amazonia")

DEP_AMAZONIA = st_crop(x = DEPARTMENTS_1, y = AMAZONIA)

Centroids

The function st_centroid() calculates the centroid of the given geometry. Let’s go to calculate them for CAUCA_MUNI.

st_crs(CAUCA_MUNI)
## Coordinate Reference System:
##   User input: WGS 84 
##   wkt:
## GEOGCRS["WGS 84",

CENT = st_centroid(CAUCA_MUNI, byid=TRUE)
## Warning: st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over geometries
plot(CENT[1])

#
plot(CAUCA_MUNI[1])
plot(CENT[1], add=T, col = "red")

#

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = CAUCA_MUNI) +
    geom_sf() +
    geom_sf(data = CENT)

Now, we can estimate the distances among the centroids. The [m] means meters, but if you need another unit, you can change the argument “which”. The operator “%>%” of the dplyr package is used to concatenate operations:

third(second(first(x))) first(x) %>% second(x) %>% third(x)

distances <- CENT %>% 
    st_cast("POINT") %>% 
    st_distance(st_centroid(CENT))

dim(distances)
## [1] 42 42
distances_2 = as.data.frame(distances)

Projections

Sometimes, you need to change the geographic projection to a planar projection. We are going to pass CAUCA_MUNI from the WGS84 geographic projection to the UTM planar projection. We can use UTM at the 18-north zone, the appropriate UTM for the Cauca, using the function spTransform. See the CRS or coordinate reference system arguments, the nomenclature of this argument is explained at here.

Figure 1. UTM zones.
CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18 = st_transform(CAUCA_MUNI, crs = 32618)
